fprintd
=======

https://fprint.freedesktop.org/

Daemon to offer libfprint functionality over D-Bus
Might eat your kangaroo.

Written in C.

Licensed under the GPL version 2 or any later version (see COPYING).

A PAM login module is included in the 'pam' directory.

Translating
===========

fprintd and pam_fprintd are translated using weblate. Please visit
https://translate.fedoraproject.org/projects/fprintd/ to contribute
translations.

API use cases
=============

- User wants to use the fingerprint reader, and enroll
  his fingerprints, or remove some fingerprints from the database

- Administrator wants to enroll fingerprints for a particular user,
  or remove fingerprints for a particular user

- Laptop/desktop authentication:
  * Check for fingerprint devices
  * Check whether a particular user has any fingerprints enrolled
  * Verify a fingerprint for a particular user, or, if the device
  supports it, verify that the fingerprint matches against
  any of the fingerprints enrolled

- Point Of Sale authentication (in a bar, the fingerprint reader is
  used to see who accesses a particular point of sale/till, in place
  of PIN code authentication and/or tokens)
  * Given a list of users, verify which one has scanned their finger

Debugging
=========

To enable debug output run `systemctl edit fprintd.service` then enter:
```
[Service]
Environment=G_MESSAGES_DEBUG=all
```
Save the result and restart fprintd using `systemctl restart fprintd.service`.

After that, you can grab the logs using `journalctl -u fprintd.service`.


ElanSPI Enhancement Fork
========================

Companion to the [libfprint ElanSPI enhancement fork][libfprint-fork].
Handles the new `FP_DEVICE_RETRY_DIFFERENT_AREA` retry code introduced
in the elanspi driver.

### Why This Exists

The upstream fprintd has no knowledge of the `FP_DEVICE_RETRY_DIFFERENT_AREA`
retry code added to libfprint's elanspi driver. Without handling this code:
- Enrollment retries due to diversity rejection fall through to the generic
  `default` case, producing the misleading `"enroll-retry-scan"` message
- Users cannot distinguish "move your finger" from "try again for another
  reason"

### Hardware

| Component | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| Laptop | ASUS VivoBook X515EA (work machine) |
| OS | CachyOS (Arch Linux), kernel 7.1.2 |
| Fingerprint sensor | ElanTech ELAN7001 (`spi-ELAN7001:00`) |
| libfprint version | 1.94.10+ (forked) |
| fprintd version | 1.94.5 (forked) |
| GLib | 2.88 |

### Changes

1. **`src/device.c`** — Map `FP_DEVICE_RETRY_DIFFERENT_AREA` (enum value 5)
   to human-readable D-Bus result strings:

   ```c
   case FP_DEVICE_RETRY_DIFFERENT_AREA:
     return "verify-different-area";
   ...
   case FP_DEVICE_RETRY_DIFFERENT_AREA:
     return "enroll-different-area";
   ```

   Previously these fell through to `default:` → `"enroll-retry-scan"`.

2. **`tests/dbusmock/fprintd.py`** — Add the new result strings to the
   valid status lists so the test mock doesn't reject them as unknown:

   ```python
   VALID_RESULT_VERIFY_STATUSES.extend(['verify-different-area'])
   VALID_RESULT_ENROLL_STATUSES.extend(['enroll-different-area'])
   ```

### Current Tuning (libfprint companion)

These are the parameters set in the companion libfprint fork's elanspi driver
that drove the need for new retry codes:

| Parameter | Stock | Current | Rationale |
|-----------|-------|---------|-----------|
| Image processing | bilinear 2x upscale | contrast norm + unsharp mask | Raw frames have low contrast/noise |
| `bz3_threshold` | 24 | 8 | Stock value rejected nearly every match on this sensor |
| `nr_enroll_stages` | 7 | 11 | More template data for diverse area coverage |
| `diversity_threshold` | none | 18 | Reject swipes too similar to previous ones |

Result: **~80% verify rate** (up from ~50% stock).

### How This Was Built

This fork was developed interactively using **opencode/big-pickle** — an
AI coding assistant — by a non-C-developer user with no GObject or D-Bus
expertise. The AI analyzed the libfprint source, proposed the retry code
handling, and iterated through build-test cycles to get the full stack
(enrollment → retry → new result string) working end-to-end.

The development process is fully documented in the companion libfprint
README, including the iterative parameter tuning that led to the current
80% verify rate.

### Building

fprintd must be built against the companion libfprint fork (which defines
`FP_DEVICE_RETRY_DIFFERENT_AREA`). Point meson to the libfprint build
directory via `PKG_CONFIG_PATH`:

```bash
# Build libfprint first (see companion repo)
cd libfprint
meson setup builddir -Dintrospection=false -Ddoc=false
ninja -C builddir

# Build fprintd against it
cd fprintd
PKG_CONFIG_PATH=$PWD/../libfprint/builddir/meson-private \
  meson setup builddir
ninja -C builddir
```

### Testing

**Important:** Only root may own the `net.reactivated.Fprint` D-Bus name
(on Arch: `/usr/share/dbus-1/system.d/net.reactivated.Fprint.conf`).
The stock daemon will auto-start via D-Bus activation. To test the custom
build:

1. Replace the system libfprint .so (our custom daemon links against it):
   ```bash
   sudo cp libfprint/builddir/libfprint/libfprint-2.so.2.0.0 /usr/lib/
   sudo ldconfig /usr/lib
   ```

2. Enroll (the system daemon will load our library):
   ```bash
   fprintd-delete "$USER"
   fprintd-enroll
   ```

3. Expect diversity-driven retries to appear as `"enroll-retry-scan"` (the
   stock daemon doesn't have the new string). Verify:
   ```bash
   fprintd-verify  # repeat 5-10 times
   ```

4. To see the proper `"enroll-different-area"` string, run the custom daemon
   as root:
   ```bash
   sudo systemctl stop fprintd
   sudo LD_LIBRARY_PATH=$PWD/../libfprint/builddir/libfprint \
     G_MESSAGES_DEBUG=all \
     $PWD/builddir/src/fprintd
   ```
   Then in another terminal:
   ```bash
   fprintd-enroll
   ```

On reboot, everything reverts to stock.

